---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="Ureview ranks arxiv math papers by expected impact = impact-if-true × proof-correctness."
  activeNav="about"
>
  <div class="container">
    <section class="page-intro page-intro--prose">
      <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span class="sep">/</span>
        <span>About</span>
      </nav>
      <span class="page-intro-eyebrow">First principles</span>
      <h1 class="page-intro-title">Two numbers per paper. Nothing else.</h1>
      <p class="page-intro-lede">
        A paper triage surface for arxiv math, built from first principles.
        Every review answers two questions and ranks the feed by their product.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="essay-shell">
    <article class="essay">
      <section class="essay-disclaimers">
        <span class="essay-kicker">The two numbers</span>
        <p>Both axes are 5-tier — <code>max / high / medium / low / minimal</code>.
        Neither LLMs nor mathematicians calibrate finer, and a unified scale keeps the feed legible.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Impact if true</strong> — if the proof goes through, how much does the result matter? <code>max</code> = field-defining (Perelman entropy formula); <code>minimal</code> = niche micro-step.</li>
          <li><strong>Proof correctness</strong> — how confident is the AI reader after a single careful pass? <code>max</code> = solid; <code>minimal</code> = almost certainly not.</li>
          <li><strong>E[impact]</strong> — a numeric proxy for ranking, derived from the two tiers. A Fields-medal paper at <code>minimal</code> correctness and a modest paper at <code>max</code> land on the same scale.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <h2 id="why">Why these two and nothing else</h2>
      <p>
        Four-dimension rubrics (soundness / presentation / significance / originality)
        invite false precision. A 7 in "presentation" is not commensurate with a 3 in
        "originality" — averaging them launders the trade-off you actually care about.
      </p>
      <p>
        Mathematicians already triage papers along exactly these two axes,
        informally. A 60-page claim of the abc conjecture and a tidy lemma in
        functional analysis are not the same kind of object, but they are
        commensurable: <em>how much should I bet, in attention, on reading
        this?</em> That is what E[impact] estimates.
      </p>

      <h2 id="how">How a review gets generated</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Papers are picked from <strong>Hugging Face Daily Papers</strong> as they surface, filtered to <code>math.*</code> arxiv categories.</li>
        <li>A language model reads the proof once and produces three things: a long-form prose reading (<code>ai_proof_review</code>), an impact score, and a correctness probability.</li>
        <li>That triplet plus arxiv metadata (title, authors, abstract verbatim, category) is published as JSON to Cloudflare R2.</li>
        <li>One review per paper. If it trends again later, we don't re-review.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="quadrants">The four quadrants</h2>
      <p>
        The browse page lets you slice the feed by quadrant. They each carry
        very different reading instructions:
      </p>
      <dl>
        <dt>Top (impact ∈ &#123;max, high&#125; × correctness ∈ &#123;max, high&#125;)</dt>
        <dd>Read carefully. Real progress on a real problem. Rare.</dd>
        <dt>Dragons (impact ∈ &#123;max, high&#125; × correctness ∈ &#123;low, minimal&#125;)</dt>
        <dd>Bold claims with shaky proofs — alleged RH proofs, Navier–Stokes regularity announcements, ABC corollaries. Read only if you enjoy hunting for the specific lemma where it breaks.</dd>
        <dt>Solid (impact ∈ &#123;medium, low, minimal&#125; × correctness ∈ &#123;max, high&#125;)</dt>
        <dd>The incremental backbone of the field. Read if you work in the area.</dd>
        <dt>The rest</dt>
        <dd>Low E[impact]. Probably skip.</dd>
      </dl>

      <h2 id="limits">What this isn't</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Not peer review, not an editorial endorsement, not a publication decision.</li>
        <li>Single-pass model output. The correctness number is an AI reader's confidence, not a community consensus.</li>
        <li>No author rebuttal flow — the arxiv link is one click away.</li>
        <li>Not a leaderboard between authors. E[impact] is a triage tool, not a metric to optimise.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked</h2>

      <h3>How can a machine estimate "correctness"?</h3>
      <p>
        Imperfectly. The tier reflects whether the proof, as written, holds
        up under a careful single read by a language model — gaps, hand-waves,
        missing absolute-convergence checks, broken induction steps. It is not
        a guarantee. <code>high</code> means the AI didn't spot a fatal gap on
        one pass; <code>minimal</code> means it spotted one and judged it
        load-bearing. Treat the tier as a prior, not a verdict.
      </p>

      <h3>Why is the Riemann hypothesis paper ranked so low?</h3>
      <p>
        Because almost-certainly-wrong × field-defining is still a tiny
        expected value. Strong claims need strong evidence; the prior on a
        one-page proof of RH is brutal. If a future RH proof actually convinces
        the AI reader, it will rocket to the top automatically.
      </p>

      <h3>How are papers picked into the queue?</h3>
      <p>
        We watch the Hugging Face Daily Papers feed and keep only the
        <code>math.*</code> entries we haven't read yet. No fixed daily quota,
        no editorial calendar.
      </p>

      <h3>Can the AI be wrong about the scores?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Calibration on impact is loose; calibration on correctness is
        looser. The scores are sharper than free-form prose but still
        compressed lossy versions of a real judgement. Open the paper.
      </p>

      <h2 id="colophon">Colophon</h2>
      <p>
        Set in <em>Fraunces</em> (variable serif, opsz + SOFT axes) and
        <em>IBM Plex Mono</em>. Published as static HTML from
        <a href="https://astro.build" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Astro</a>;
        review JSON hosted on Cloudflare R2.
        Math is rendered with <a href="https://katex.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">KaTeX</a>.
        Hand-written CSS; no client framework.
      </p>
    </article>

    <aside class="essay-toc" aria-label="On this page">
      <span class="essay-toc-label">On this page</span>
      <ol>
        <li><a href="#why">Why these two</a></li>
        <li><a href="#how">How a review is made</a></li>
        <li><a href="#quadrants">The four quadrants</a></li>
        <li><a href="#limits">What this isn't</a></li>
        <li><a href="#faq">Frequently asked</a></li>
        <li><a href="#colophon">Colophon</a></li>
      </ol>
    </aside>
  </div>
</Layout>
